  "time_ut": 1657511146,
  "original_lang": "ta",
  "original_title": "\u0b87\u0ba8\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b87\u0bb0\u0bbe\u0ba3\u0bc1\u0bb5 \u0b9a\u0bb0\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bcd\u0b9a\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bc8 \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb3\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bae\u0ba3\u0bbf\u0baf \u0b9a\u0bc1\u0bb5\u0bbe\u0bae\u0bbf",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Subramaniam Swamy, who sparked controversy in the Indian Army",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "The BJP has asked former Prime Minister Mahinda Rajapaksa and President Gotaya Rajapaksa to send the Indian Army to support them if they request them. Subramanian Swamy, the senior leader of , had posted the comment on his official Twitter handle.",
        "It said, \u201cBoth Gotabaya and Mahinda Rajapaksa were elected with absolute majority in free elections. How can India allow a mob to subvert such a legitimate election?\u201d He questioned that.",
        "\u201cThen no democracy in our neighborhood will be safe. \"We are ready to provide India's military assistance when the Rajapaksas demand it,\" Subramanian Swamy had said.",
        "As the post sparked controversy, the Indian High Commission in Colombo has announced that it categorically denies media and social media speculation about India sending its army to Sri Lanka.",
        "\"The Government of India does not stand by these statements and such comments and India stands with the people of Sri Lanka who seek to realize their aspirations for prosperity and progress through democratic means and values, established institutions and constitutional framework,\" the spokesperson of the Ministry of External Affairs of India has already made clear. As mentioned in the said Twitter post.",
        "The High Commission would like to categorically deny speculative reports in sections of media and social media about India sending her troops to Sri Lanka. These reports and such views are also not in keeping with the position of"
      ],
